The Fort Calhoun Pioneers were on a power trip Thursday night. 
After Ashland-Greenwood went ahead 2-1 in the top of third, sophomore Hannah Warner stepped up to the plate and blasted her first home run of the season over the right-field fence to put the Pioneers ahead 3-2. 
Freshmen Jordan Wear and Courtney Baxter followed with two of the hardest hit balls you'll see in high school softball. Wear's a screaming line-drive single and Baxter's a rope off the fence for a double. 
Enter senior Erin Schulz. 
There are two fences at Fort Calhoun's softball field, one that's temporary and sits about 210 feet from home plate and the chain link fence another 75 feet behind that. Schulz nearly cleared them both. The towering shot to center was Schulz's fourth of the season and first since Aug. 24 th . It also put the Pioneers ahead 6-2. 
Fort Calhoun would coast from there, as sophomore pitcher Kloey Appel worked out of a couple sticky situations to earn the win, her 12 th of the season. The Pioneers added two runs in the fourth and one in the fifth for a 9-2 win. 
Baxter fueled the Fort Calhoun offense, which outhit the Bluejays 9-5, by going 3-4 with three RBIs. Warner, who is hitting .488 this season, was 2-4. Freshmen Zoe King, Wear, junior Lauren Nelson and seniors Jordan Coulter and Schulz all finished the game with a hit. 
Fort Calhoun improved to 12-8 and will travel to Omaha Duchesne on Monday evening. 
Fort Calhoun 9 Ashland-Greenwood 2
